##Getting Setup

First, we need to set up our environment so that we run R code and can connect to the remote Netezza system.

I need to load the __`rmagic`__ extension to establish connectivity with R.

outputs.text:
The rmagic extension is already loaded. To reload it, use:
  %reload_ext rmagic

cells.source: You will see the prefix __`%R`__ (for a single line) or __`%%R`__ for multiple lines of R code.  Any code with these in front will be passed through directly to R.

cells.input:
%%R

library(nzr)
library(nza)
library(ggplot2)
library(colorspace)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(gridExtra)

cells.source: These commands use an ODBC connection to connect to the Netezza machine.  If you are running this code on your own machine, there should be a DSN named __`NZSQL`__ already created with valid connection information for your particular server.

outputs.text:
Cartridge ' r_ae ' is not installed
 
 

On the spus: R 3.0.2
On the host: R 3.0.2

cells.source:
We can safely ignore this message.  The R functionality is working just fine on my system, it seems to always return an odd error about the cartridge not being installed.

##Connecting to Data

The __`nz.data.frame()`__ function creates a link to table on the remote system.  

It is important to understand that no data was transferred between the remote Netezza system and the R host with this command.  This will DRAMATICALLY speed up analysis for large data sets, especially those with million+ observations.

The __`CALL_SP`__ function is a simple wrapper that lets you call stored procedures on the Netezza system without any SQL.  __`DROP_ALL_MODELS`__ is a database stored procedure that clears out any old data and lets us start fresh.

It is also important to understand that we are creating real, usable R objects that have metadata about the database objects and can be manipulated by the R environment without needing SQL.

outputs.text:
SELECT "ID","V1","V2","V3","V4","V5" FROM CLUSTER_DEMO 
SELECT "ID","V1","V2","V3","V4","V5" FROM CLUSTER_DEMO_OTHER 
[1] "CLUSTER_DEMO"

cells.source: Here is an example of how you can look at the information in more detail in R.  Note that this data was cached when we first made our __`nz.data.frame`__, there isn't any data transfer being done.
The same thing can also be done with SQL, but the syntax isn't nearly as elegant.

cells.input:
%%R 

nzQuery("SELECT COUNT(*) FROM analysis_db..cluster_demo")
nzQuery("SELECT attnum,attname FROM _v_relation_column WHERE NAME=UPPER('cluster_demo') ORDER BY attnum ASC")
nzQuery("SELECT COUNT(*) FROM _v_relation_column WHERE NAME=UPPER('cluster_demo') ")

cells.source:
The __`nzQuery()`__ function lets you get down and dirty with SQL if you really want to.  This can be really  powerful for large, production level optimizations, but isn't strictly necessary.  

##Working With the Data

When working with raw data, one of the conundrums is data movement.  Clearly, it is faster and more accurate to work with a complete data set.  However, this can be very expensive to move data over a network.

In our case, we are going to build a small random sample of our data strictly for visualization, about __`5%`__.  It will be small enough to transfer to the R server and large enough to give us what we need for display.

cells.input:
%%R 

callSP("RANDOM_SAMPLE", 
          intable="analysis_db..cluster_demo", 
          fraction=.05,
          outtable="analysis_db..cluster_demo_sample", 
          outclear="true", 
          replace="false")

my_db_data_sample = nz.data.frame("cluster_demo_sample")

cells.source: All the data is still on the server at this point.  We need to make a pointer to it using the __`nz.data.frame()`__ function and then bring it to the R server using the __`as.data.frame()`__ function.

cells.input:
%%R -w 50 -h 25 -u cm

plot(as.data.frame(my_db_data_sample))

# Look ma, data transfer with no SQL!

cells.source:
So, let's recap.  We have ...

- Done our first step in exploratory data analysis on a database server.
- Created a random sample of a larger data set.
- Built a scatter plot matrix locally.
- Only used standard R syntax.
- Had minimal data movement across the network. 

###Very cool.###

Putting on our Data Scientist hats, we can see that have a dataset with:

1. An observation id (called __`ID`__)
2. 5 numeric variables (called __`V1`__-__`V5`__)

The interaction between __`V1`__ and __`V2`__ seems interesting, the others seem pretty random.  Let's grab just those variables and look at them exclusively.

In case you are scoring at home, I did just do the data transfer for the sample a second time.  In your code, you should set a variable to the full sample dataset and then use __`as.data.frame`__ to bring it over just once.  I was demonstrating the ability to coerce SQL into data, not trying to write particularly efficient code.

##Modeling the Data

After looking at the data, it seems clear that there is some order in the variables __`V1`__ and __`V2`__.  It would make sense to explore some clustering here to see if that is truly the case.

We can take advantage of the in-database functions to do our heavy lifting on the remote machine.  INZA has both the `K-Means` and `Two-Step` clustering algorithms, depending on if you want to do supervised or unsupervised learning.

The __`nzTwoStep`__ function is assuming that the "ID" variable uniquely identifies each observation.  The function calculated using the CPU, RAM, and disk resources on the Netezza server, not the R server.  However, __`my_clusters`__ is a fully functioning R model.
You can introspect `my_clusters` just like any other R object.

It looks like the __`nzTwoStep`__ sees four clusters.

Also, in __`my_clusters`__, the __`model`__ description is important, as this is a unique identifier that links back to the original model specifications.

If we wanted to use this model again on other data with underlying SQL, we could use this to make sure we had the right parameters.  You might see this happen in a production environment.  However, if we are using R, we can apply our model using the __`predict()`__ function.

Let's apply the __`my_clusters`__ model to what is contained in __`my_other_db_data`__ to demonstrate.

___Again, no SQL required!___
  
Of course, if we wanted to see the actual data, we could just use a command like __`print(as.data.frame(predicted.results))`__.  However, there isn't any real need to do it, as we know that the data is safe on the server.

##Visualization##

Now, let's make some pretty pictures.  If we are going to use R to do our visualization, we need to transfer the actual data to the server. So, we should expect these cells to run a bit slower.

Keep in mind that we only need to this once, and typically that would be done in the beginning of our analysis.  I am showing how to do it here in its entirety for the sake of completeness.

First, let's get a small sample, say 2.5%.

cells.input:
%%R

# get a random sample of the data, without replacement
callSP("RANDOM_SAMPLE", 
          intable="analysis_db..cluster_demo", 
          fraction=.025,
          outtable="analysis_db..cluster_demo_sample_bigger", 
          outclear="true", 
          replace="false")

# bring down the actual data to the R server.
my_db_data_sample_small = nz.data.frame("cluster_demo_sample")
data.sample.small = as.data.frame(my_db_data_sample_small)

# identify the clusters that this data resides in
predicted.results.small = predict(my_clusters,my_db_data_sample_small, "ID")
data.sample.small.results = as.data.frame(predicted.results.small)

cells.source: Next, let's get a bigger sample, say 25%.

cells.input:
%%R

# get a random sample of the data, without replacement
callSP("RANDOM_SAMPLE", 
          intable="analysis_db..cluster_demo", 
          fraction=.25,
          outtable="analysis_db..cluster_demo_sample_bigger", 
          outclear="true", 
          replace="false")

# bring down the actual data to the R server.
my_db_data_sample_bigger = nz.data.frame("cluster_demo_sample_bigger")
data.sample.bigger = as.data.frame(my_db_data_sample_bigger)

# identify the clusters that this data resides in
predicted.results.bigger = predict(my_clusters, my_db_data_sample_bigger, "ID")
data.sample.bigger.results = as.data.frame(predicted.results.bigger)

cells.source: We merge the cluster data with the actual data, giving us something that can be displayed with something like __`ggplot`__.  We will leverage the cluster id for the specifications for colors in our displays using the R __`cut`__ command.

cells.input:
%%R

data.sample.small.display = merge(data.sample.small.results, data.sample.small, by="ID")
small.colors <- cut(data.sample.small.display$CLUSTER_ID, length(my_clusters$centers))

data.sample.bigger.display = merge(data.sample.bigger.results, data.sample.bigger, by="ID")
bigger.colors <- cut(data.sample.bigger.display$CLUSTER_ID, length(my_clusters$centers))

cells.source:
Now we have our data on our server, in memory.

We are going to want to plot similar points with similar colors.  So, we use the R function __`cut`__ to turn  the cluster id into a color group.  Here is the are both samples:

cells.input:
%%R -w 50 -h 25 -u cm

s = ggplot(data.sample.small.display, aes (x = V1, y = V2, col=small.colors) ) 
b = ggplot(data.sample.bigger.display, aes (x = V1, y = V2, col=bigger.colors) ) 

s1 = s + geom_point() + ggtitle('Small Sample, Auto Cluster')
s2 = s + stat_density2d () + ggtitle('Small Sample Contours, Auto Cluster')
b1 = b + geom_point() + ggtitle('Large Sample, Auto Cluster')
b2 = b + stat_density2d () + ggtitle('Large Sample Contours, Auto Cluster')

grid.arrange(s1,s2,b1,b2,ncol=2,nrow=2)

cells.source:
Now, this looks a bit odd.  We trusted the Two-Step algorithm to identify our clusters, and it did.  However, there seems to be quite a bit of overlap between them, which makes me think there are only two clusters.  As is so often the case, we need a human to effectively interpret the results.

# Getting More Specific

The only change we really need to make is to add another argument (__`k=2`__) to the  __`nzTwoStep()`__ function.  Here is all the code in a single cell.

cells.input:
%%R -w 50 -h 25 -u cm

# Make a model of the clusters inside the database
my_clusters = nzTwoStep(my_db_data, k=2, id="ID")

# get a random sample of the data, without replacement
callSP("RANDOM_SAMPLE", 
          intable="analysis_db..cluster_demo", 
          fraction=.25,
          outtable="analysis_db..cluster_demo_sample_final", 
          outclear="true", 
          replace="false")

# bring down the actual data to the R server.
my_db_data_sample_final = nz.data.frame("cluster_demo_sample_final")
data.sample.final = as.data.frame(my_db_data_sample_final)

# identify the clusters that this data resides in
predicted.results.final = predict(my_clusters, my_db_data_sample_final, "ID")
data.sample.final.results = as.data.frame(predicted.results.final)

# define the colors for each clusters, based on the unique cluster ID's defined by nzTwoStep
data.sample.final.display = merge(data.sample.final.results, data.sample.final, by="ID")
final.colors <- cut(data.sample.final.display$CLUSTER_ID, length(my_clusters$centers))

# plot the data and see the results.
combo <- ggplot(data.sample.final.display, aes (x = V1, y = V2))
combo <- combo + geom_density2d(colour="gray60")
combo <- combo + geom_point(aes(col=final.colors), alpha=0.8)
combo <- combo + ggtitle('Combination Plot, k=2')

plot(combo, width = 5, height = 3, units = 'in', res = 300)

cells.source:
##Let the Awesome Flow

I hope this shows some of the powerful things you can do when you combine a best of breed language like R with best of breed analytic hardware like Netezza.

We were able to:

- Do exploratory data analysis remotely.
- Create a random sample of a larger data set.
- Build a model of an arbitrarily large dataset without having to ever move the data to R.
- Visualize our data locally.
- Adjust our clustering model and repeat our predictions.
- Use standard R syntax.
- Minimize data movement.

Data movement is typically the most time-intensive part of data science.  You can do everything you need to and avoid unecessary data transfers by doing your analytics in the database.

###Very, very, very cool.###
